olson@umbc.edu (Bryan G. Olson; CMSC (G)) writes:

>Miguel Angel Gallardo Ortiz (mgallar@asterix.fi.upm.es) wrote:

>: We are working in a new patent in order to use CD ROMS with random bits as
>: a one time pad key, in order to offer "perfect secret" on a cheap basis.  

>: Please let me know any device related with this one that you know,[...]

>I don't know that anyone has built a CD ROM one-time-pad (OTP) device,
>though it has been discussed here before.

>My opinion was (and still is) that CD ROM is a terrible medium for the
>OTP key stream.  First, you want exactly two copies of the random
>stream.  CD ROM has an economic advantage only for large runs.
>Second, you want to destroy the part of the stream already used.  CD
>ROM has no erase facilities, outside of physical destruction of the
>entire disk.

The man as a point.  I think that magnetic tape would be better.  An 8mm 
data cartridge can hold 7 Gigabytes of data (uncompressed, off the shelf 
technology today), would cost a lot less in small quantities, and be 
easier to erase (even if you overwrote it several times) and reuse.
